derivation.yuyuan_name: late Middle English: via French from Latin impenetrabilis, from in- 'not' + penetrabilis 'able to be pierced', from the verb penetrare (see penetrate)

entry.tran: 不能穿过的;刺不进的;透不过的
entry.def: If you describe something such as a barrier or a forest as impenetrable, you mean that it is impossible or very difficult to get through.

example.ex: ...the Caucasus range, an almost impenetrable barrier between Europe and Asia.
example.tran: 高加索山脉,几乎难以穿越的欧亚屏障

entry.def: If you describe something such as a book or a theory as impenetrable, you are emphasizing that it is impossible or very difficult to understand.

example.tran: 他的书出了名的晦涩难懂。

means.word_mean: 1. not admitting of penetration or passage into or through;
2. permitting little if any light to pass through because of denseness of matter;
